Oh, Polly, I feel your pain!  There is a way to use larger squares and cut
them diagonally (once or twice as needed to keep the edges from being bias
on the edges and corners) so you don't end up with bias edges, but it's too
late for that now.  I'd suggest adding a border cut on the lengthwise grain.
Measure what your bias edge *should* be- without stretching- for each block
and then measure and mark the border at those same intervals, match the
marks on the top and the border and pin carefully.  Sew the border on with
the bias edge on the bottom against the feeddogs.  That should get you a
stable border edge.  Then continue as usual.  Good luck.....

Leslie &amp; The Furbabies in MO.

